		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Deconstructing Sam, Son of Hamfest<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.62)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=2214'>Michael "mc9457" Carr</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=2214&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Well, it seems it is time to tear apart another card. This series (as it may become) will not focus on how to use a card, but rather why it is not the be all end all, and how it can be beaten. Last time I deconstructed the common Balrog. Tonight, I will have fun tearing apart Sam, Son of Hamfast. <br />
<br />
First, lets look at the basics.<br />
<br />
He is a Shire Hobbit which gives him some distinct advantages: Talent for Not Being Seen, Hobbit Intuition, Hobbit Stealth, the site that subtracts 1 from his twilight cost, Bounder.<br />
<br />
He is a ringbearer (or at least would be if Frodo ever bites the big one).<br />
<br />
He has a resistance of 5. That is good, but not Frodo good.<br />
<br />
He is power 3.<br />
<br />
He has a health of 4.<br />
<br />
He has a twilight of 2.<br />
<br />
He has an Aragorn Signet.<br />
<br />
During the Fellowship phase of the game, he has the opportunity to remove Burdens by exerting like a madman.<br />
<br />
He can be pulled via the Green Dragon Inn.<br />
<br />
Now banning all other potential future cards to come out (including league promos), and taking into consideration the whole Sam/Rosie/Gaffer/Hobbit Party Guest/Rare Frodo hobbit healing ring, lets take a look at just how week this little hobbit is.<br />
<br />
Before I begin, a brief overview of how the Hobbit Healing Ring works:<br />
<br />
Bid high to get your starting site (wether it be Prancing Pony to get out Aragorn or Green Hill Country to get your healing ring out cheaply or Green Dragon Inn so you can play Sam without starting with him). Then exert Sam to remove Burdens. Transfer these wounds to Rosie and The Gaffer, who transfers at least 1 of them to the Hobbit Party Guest. Beginning of your next turn, Hobbit Party Guest heals himself, Rare Frodo heals the one with a<br />
wound. Continue this trick until you have no Burdens and no wounds.<br />
<br />
Power of 3.<br />
<br />
Wow. This is really bad. Since doubling a characters power complete kills that character off, having low power is really bad. Have I mentioned how bad it is? Okay, lets briefly go over who can&#39;t overwhelm Sam, pump cards<br />
excluded: Uruk Savage, Goblin Archer, Goblin Backstabber, Goblin Runner, Goblin Sneak, Orc Ambusher. 7 minions out of an estimated 58 total minions. And of those, the ones that see the most play are Orc Ambusher and Goblin Runner. And if you see a Runner, you can bet you will see more minions. This means only a large fellowship can defend Sam and Frodo, or at least one that has a few Defender +1 characters in it.<br />
<br />
Health of 4.<br />
<br />
Nothing new here. All hobbit companions have this, as does Aragorn and Gandalf. So nothing special here. This allows him to exert a lot to remove burdens (at least 6 a turn with the Healing Ring in effect). Not really a downside, but it does give the user a feel he can wound/exert Sam more often then they would Legalos. This can be used to your (shadow) advantage, as I will explain later.<br />
<br />
Shire Hobbit.<br />
<br />
Hobbits are by far the easiest hobbits to get to site 5 with. There are so many tricks you can pull with them. Whether it be running away from battle via Hobbit Stealth/Intuition, reducing twighlight via A Talent for Not Being Seen, boosting the power to overwhelm from 2 times to 3 times, or infinite healing rungs, hobbits can really frustrate even the most powerful of minions. However, here is their innate problems: First they can take more then one wound per turn. Currently there is no card that limits damage taken to one wound per skirmish phase (as there are for Gondor and Dwarves). Hobbits have no condition removal tactics, which kills versus Blade Tip/Black Breath, Worry, Desperate Defense of the Ring, etc. From site 6 on, they are easily trounced. At that point no one is roaming, and the stealths and intuitions turn from run away cards to pump cards. They rely way too much on skirmish and stealth events, as well as weapon cards and allies, to win. This can easily be countered by just about every culture out there. Uruk Hai have Sarumon&#39;s Snows to cancel skirmish events, and Wariness to cancel stealth events. Moria has Relentless to cancel stealth events. Ringwraith has Beauty is Fading to remove allies (as well as Sam if there are no allies or conditions - granted the number of times this will happen is rare, but it could), Fear to remove allies, Their Power Is In Terror to remove allies in the maneuver phase (by this time they will have already exerted their hobbit healing ring to exhaustion, TPIIT will in turn kill each of these allies). Sauron has Seeking It Always to cancel stealth conditions. For the weapons, Uruk Hai has Troop of Uruk Hai, and Ringwraith has Ulaire Cantea who can exert to discard a possession. Breeland Forest PREVENTS stealth events from being played completely. And that is open and available to every minion.<br />
<br />
Being a hobbit also makes him vunerable to Orc Assassin, which thanks to Sam, forces the Free People to assign either Sam or Frodo (if they are both out at the same time, which in most cases, will occur). Get two of these guys out, and unless the Free People have a Pump card or a weapon or Bounder, Sam and Frodo will die.<br />
<br />
He Can Be A Ringbearer.<br />
<br />
Sure this seems good at first, but lets examine why it is also bad. First, he can not use Power According To His Stature (PATHS) until he has the ring, which kills. An early Moria Swarm will remove any possibility of using<br />
PATHS with Sam. Assign intelligently and you can remove this hobbit early. It also does not protect him early game from the various cards that say &quot;Exert X to cause X to occur (except to the Ring Bearer)&quot; There are tons of these cards, and a lot that are good. Use them early to hurt Sam. <br />
<br />
He has an Aragorn Signet.<br />
<br />
By far the most annoying part of this little hobbit is the fact that he can easily be healed every turn by Aragorn at no cost. None. <br />
<br />
He can remove Burdens by Exerting.<br />
<br />
Benefit with consequences. Exerting is why Sam is not Broken at all and why he does not kill a burden deck.  Exerting brings Sam that much closer to exhaustion and death. Why? Explained briefly. Yes he can remove up to 6<br />
burdens a turn if the hobbit healing ring is in full effect. However, this will not happen every turn. And not every game is won with 10 burdens. Despair and Irresitable Shadow set up alternative win situations where it only requires 12 total dead companions and burdens or 5 burdens and no cards in draw deck to win. At site 9 you can easily rack up 5 burdens and deck your opponent.<br />
<br />
How to beat Sam senseless.<br />
<br />
There are a couple of strategies here, but I will focus on the most obvious.<br />
<br />
Exert Sam.<br />
<br />
How do you do that? Easily, especially with Sauron. Under the Watching Eye. Condition. &quot;Exert a Tracker and play in your support area. Every time the Free People move to a site, they must exert someone.&quot; Play 4 of these (since they are not unique) and you are pretty much guaranteed to hit Sam at least once during the end of the Fellowship phase.<br />
<br />
How else can you do that? There are several sites that require you to exert when you move to them: Midgewater Marshes (exert every hobbit); Moria Lake (exert Frodo or two companions); Dwarrowdelf Chamber (exert Gimli or two companions); Silverlode Banks (unless you can spot a ranger, exert all companions).<br />
<br />
Direct Damage Sam to Death.<br />
<br />
Harder to do (requiring more rares), but can be done. Lets look at a standard situation with Sam.<br />
<br />
Start the game with Frodo and Aragorn. Bid 3 and win. Start the Green Dragon Inn. Exert Frodo to play Sam from Draw deck (2 twilight). Exert Sam 2 times to remove all Burdens. Move to site 2 (Midgewater Marshes) (3 twilight). Exert Sam and Frodo. Play Orc Inquisitor (power 9, 3 health). During Maneuver Phase, play Hate (exert Orc Inquisitor) on Sam. Sam dies.<br />
<br />
Warning: This is vunerable to What Are They?<br />
<br />
Prevent Sam from Healing.<br />
<br />
Two cultures can currently prevent healing. Ringwraith has Blackbreath, which prevents healing everywhere. Sauron has You Bring Great Evil which prevents healing at Sanctuaries. This can also be used alternatively on<br />
Frodo, preventing Burden removals. <br />
<br />
So as you can see, Sam is not the end all to all burden decks. Yes he hinders them, but he can be beat. Easily. He is just one more thing to consider when constructing your deck. Remember you won&#39;t see him in every deck, but the above strategies can also be applied to other characters that need to exert to do cool things (rare Gimli, rare Legolas, rare Aragorn, Aragorn&#39;s bow).<br />
<br />
Til next time. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3191&view=1&PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=...328fedb22570524062aeb1303'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
